TITLE: Labor board issues complaint against Starbucks in firing of 7 workers.
SUMMARY: The workers had been seeking to unionize a store in Memphis.

TITLE: Atlanta Apple Store Workers Are the First to Formally Seek a Union
SUMMARY: The petition for a union vote continues a trend of organizing at service-sector employers like Starbucks and Amazon.

TITLE: World Economic Outlook Dims as War and Pandemic Cast a Pall
SUMMARY: The International Monetary Fund’s new World Economic Outlook expects growth to slow to 3.6 percent this year. The group is one of many to slash their forecasts recently.

TITLE: How a Dollar General Employee Went Viral on TikTok
SUMMARY: Mary Gundel loved managing a store in Tampa, Fla. But when she detailed its challenges on social media, the company — and fellow employees — took notice.

TITLE: Jim Farley Tries to Reinvent Ford and Catch Up to Elon Musk and Tesla
SUMMARY: Ford’s chief executive is about to introduce an electric F-150 pickup truck that could determine whether the automaker can survive and thrive in an industry dominated by Tesla.

TITLE: Disney, Built on Fairy Tales and Fantasy, Confronts the Real World
SUMMARY: The entertainment behemoth spent decades avoiding even the whiff of controversy. But it has increasingly been drawn into the partisan political fray.

TITLE: What Will Happen if Russia Defaults on Its Debt?
SUMMARY: The ultimate arbiter of a sovereign default is an open question but markets may have the final word.

TITLE: How Rising Mortgage Rates Are Affecting the Housing Market
SUMMARY: Mortgage costs have jumped as the Federal Reserve has raised rates. With higher rates come fewer offers.

TITLE: Biden to Nominate Michael Barr as Fed Vice Chair for Supervision
SUMMARY: Mr. Barr faced pushback from progressives when his name was floated for a different position.

TITLE: Fuel Prices Send Airfares Higher, but Travelers Seem Ready to Pay
SUMMARY: Supplies are not keeping up with demand, and costs may go higher, experts say.

TITLE: Gopuff Buys Time for Its 30-Minutes-or-Less Delivery Promise
SUMMARY: The $15 billion rapid-delivery start-up decided to do business differently from rivals like Instacart. A changing environment is testing its model.

TITLE: Supply Chain Hurdles Will Outlast Covid Pandemic, White House Says
SUMMARY: The administration’s economic advisers see climate change and other factors complicating global trade patterns for years to come.

TITLE: U.S. Tries New Tactic to Protect Workers’ Pay: Antitrust Law
SUMMARY: The Justice Department is using antitrust law to charge employers with colluding to hold down wages. The move adds to a barrage of civil challenges.

TITLE: A Fed governor says the latest inflation data reaffirms the case for big rate increases.
SUMMARY: The central bank is contemplating a half-point rate move in May. Christopher J. Waller, a Fed governor, said inflation data may justify big increases in months to come.

TITLE: Britain’s inflation rate climbed to 7 percent, the highest in 30 years.
SUMMARY: Household budgets are squeezed as wage increases are not keeping pace with rising prices.

TITLE: Actors in ‘Waitress’ Tour Seek to Join Labor Union
SUMMARY: Employees of a nonunion production are seeking improved compensation and safety protocols, saying a union version of the same musical pays better.

TITLE: Biden to Allow Higher-Ethanol E15 Gas to Be Sold All Summer
SUMMARY: The White House estimated that the move would allow Americans to save 10 cents a gallon at the approximately 2,300 stations in the country that offer the blend known as E15.

TITLE: Inflation Hits Fastest Pace Since 1981, at 8.5% Through March
SUMMARY: Gasoline weighed heavily in the increases, while prices moderated in several categories. Some economists say the overall rate may have peaked.

TITLE: Few Cars, Lots of Customers: Why Autos Are an Inflation Risk
SUMMARY: Economists are betting that supply chains for all kinds of goods will heal, shortages will ease and price gains will slow. Cars are a wild card in those forecasts.

TITLE: Starbucks Union Campaign Continues Its Momentum
SUMMARY: Workers at six more stores in upstate New York have voted to unionize.
